vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. vuln_name: Insecure response with wildcard '*' in Access-Control-Allow-Origin
vuln_desc:
Description: Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) is a mechanism that allows restricted resources (e.g. fonts) on a web page to be requested from another domain outside the domain from which the resource originated. The Access-Control-Allow-Origin header indicates whether a resource can be shared based by returning the value of the Origin request header, "*", or "null" in the response.

If a website responds with Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * the requested resource allows sharing with every origin. Therefore, any website can make XHR (XMLHTTPRequest) requests to your site and access the responses. It's not recommended to use the Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * header.Impact: Any website can make XHR requests to your site and access the responses.Request: GET /docs/ HTTP/1.1Accept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: helloorange.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21Connection: Keep-alive

Description: Apache Tomcat default installation contains the "/examples" directory which has many example servlets and JSPs.Some of these examples are a security risk and should not be deployed on a production server.
The Sessions Example servlet (installed at /examples/servlets/servlet/SessionExample) allows session manipulation. Because the session is global this servlet poses a big security risk as an attacker can potentitally become an administrator by manipulating its session.Impact: Bypassing HttpOnly Cookies protection, CSRF cookies manipulation, Session manipulation.Request: GET /examples/servlets/servlet/SessionExample HTTP/1.1Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: mscase.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Connection: Keep-alive:

vuln_desc:
The value of the Referer HTTP header is used to perform an HTTP redirect. The payload http://a703e8u4l1t/a?https://126.177.67.118/resetuj-haslo.jsf was submitted in the Referer HTTP header. This caused a redirection to the following URL:
  • http://a703e8u4l1t/a?https://126.177.67.118/resetuj-haslo.jsf


The original request used the POST method, however it was possible to convert the request to use the GET method, to enable viable exploitation in a phishing attack.

Because the data used in the redirection is submitted within a header, the application's behavior is unlikely to be directly useful in lending credibility to a phishing attack. This limitation considerably mitigates the impact of the vulnerability.

The application publishes a Flash cross-domain policy which uses a wildcard to specify allowed domains, and allows access from specific other domains.

Using a wildcard to specify allowed domains means that any domain matching the wildcard expression can perform two-way interaction with this application. You should only use this policy if you fully trust every possible web site that may reside on a domain which matches the wildcard expression.

Allowing access from specific domains means that web sites on those domains can perform two-way interaction with this application. You should only use this policy if you fully trust the specific domains allowed by the policy.

Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return a frame-ancestors directive in the Content-Security-Policy header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The frame-ancestors directives can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. Description: This script is possibly vulnerable to Cross Site Scripting (XSS) attacks.

Cross site scripting (also referred to as XSS) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to send malicious code (usually in the form of Javascript) to another user.Because a browser cannot know if the script should be trusted or not, it will execute the script in the user context allowing the attacker to access any cookies or session tokens retained by the browser.Impact: Malicious users may inject JavaScript, VBScript, ActiveX, HTML or Flash into a vulnerable application to fool a user in order to gather data from them.An attacker can steal the session cookie and take over the account, impersonating the user.It is also possible to modify the content of the page presented to the user.Request: GET /vouchers/referrals/AUTOMATIONE2E?withEligibility=true'%22()%26%25%3Cacx%3E%3CScRiPt%20%3EBMoU(9148)%3C/ScRiPt%3E HTTP/1.1Referer: https://dev-public-gateway.dopapp.pl/vouchers/referrals/AUTOMATIONE2E?withEligibility=trueAccept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: dev-public-gateway.dopapp.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Proxy-Connection: Keep-aliveAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCIgOiAiSldUIiwia2lkIiA6ICJBUTVpRk5fUTgwc2Fybm56dkVWLXkyTlIzZXpZV0JVTDd5SHgwSDNiVnFRIn0..hx-MLZsXpSsJcuZBxjGH_wxhc7I_MGMRunyZ-kpjtXHYwtfHi2k7vjD6SnsYMcZ1pzhQi3Tlvxse3GeWLFJYE1lJcPnlZXhazNjjgF8tfpWLnu9b9SiUwXRJyZm0ukQe1tmA8x82_qb6eUliqGHi4yD3lgeSFQEWLdRk5qEH0td87r_YkONKg1V12XP5a57by3V004KtqTuRToDw5HdYQNayRJVDHSX3TsyY37mkOP1yAq_Z6za67dM62BBWZ6mYMJ2EEuChv_xdJxpA_A_wJX25LDlabhQragEYgZgw7apddf3ZGESL5xyUMcp5S2A0ftPyRE8llJdYIraRqbxX1Qapikey: 523c0c49-6e32-43a3-9c38-46d0e78d285dContent-Type: application/json

vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. vuln_desc:
Description: This script is possibly vulnerable to Cross Site Scripting (XSS) attacks.

Cross site scripting (also referred to as XSS) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to send malicious code (usually in the form of Javascript) to another user.Because a browser cannot know if the script should be trusted or not, it will execute the script in the user context allowing the attacker to access any cookies or session tokens retained by the browser.Impact: Malicious users may inject JavaScript, VBScript, ActiveX, HTML or Flash into a vulnerable application to fool a user in order to gather data from them.An attacker can steal the session cookie and take over the account, impersonating the user.It is also possible to modify the content of the page presented to the user.Request: GET /offers?active=true'%22()%26%25%3Cacx%3E%3CScRiPt%20%3EHuTd(9245)%3C/ScRiPt%3E&category=VIDEOPASS HTTP/1.1Referer: https://dev-public-gateway.dopapp.pl/offers?category=VIDEOPASS&active=trueAccept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: dev-public-gateway.dopapp.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Proxy-Connection: Keep-aliveAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCIgOiAiSldUIiwia2lkIiA6ICJBUTVpRk5fUTgwc2Fybm56dkVWLXkyTlIzZXpZV0JVTDd5SHgwSDNiVnFRIn0..MrLzOK5gwaGvzMuTacBBM6NNNdf27ua2bypOrMUxWHPc-xN89Cazna8HZHRtsNIUanVW8GvikDf7AKK338Tbd2U5bBfqgTbyIlX7qV_8391-P8Pfo-8R_qpDfcAtido2ffLFixoGIE3_NAKYYiOPE9f0mT5AXuCGsHnld3dB1UvAUYxajH3dXDPcsF90TdmwjMH0QVbzpsDIa4zbkFdIfPC8R48jWVICgVl8XEPVhEYYqg47t9RWWGDeCAre83Xu4AGHeRBgVlGYbBEH_BGYEpLP2ifyl29eVv4E9e0o7NwBGOGqhN2SE1gVeChcn50Z4cIZ7j5T7u-KNy4izwNK6gContent-Type: application/jsonX-Correlation-Id: test_automation_20200417_023353_c56t918niuapikey: 523c0c49-6e32-43a3-9c38-46d0e78d285d

Cross site scripting (also referred to as XSS) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to send malicious code (usually in the form of Javascript) to another user.Because a browser cannot know if the script should be trusted or not, it will execute the script in the user context allowing the attacker to access any cookies or session tokens retained by the browser.Impact: Malicious users may inject JavaScript, VBScript, ActiveX, HTML or Flash into a vulnerable application to fool a user in order to gather data from them.An attacker can steal the session cookie and take over the account, impersonating the user.It is also possible to modify the content of the page presented to the user.Request: GET /users/e3184f50-7b17-47f4-a0fe-5a41e66eccfe/messages?page=1'%22()%26%25%3Cacx%3E%3CScRiPt%20%3E7UR8(9312)%3C/ScRiPt%3E HTTP/1.1Referer: https://dev-public-gateway.dopapp.pl/users/e3184f50-7b17-47f4-a0fe-5a41e66eccfe/messagesAccept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: dev-public-gateway.dopapp.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Proxy-Connection: Keep-aliveAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCIgOiAiSldUIiwia2lkIiA6ICJBUTVpRk5fUTgwc2Fybm56dkVWLXkyTlIzZXpZV0JVTDd5SHgwSDNiVnFRIn0..UxDt_4e0dRSE_S8iEla1I_KAkrv__Wkwo9cj5lvaGFrV4sT5u6Q8hoW3SeljrCOMksYJn-vZYXiuXQkkj8lKyMRJi7dBY2PgBvo8aKWiz9WxjVP__uoEEvXjcstEiLZEke84R78jUyqQU4VEATtViUa_EtEYHnwGhbSjHgH2e7y8z6kPewnguM04pkeBUdGp_KQyPXbZOgktAhssAwCK3b4Mh_2eqli547ZKy1JQ1Xfc_dour42xYuPquT_Aplq4LVKw6QxZFFBXVde_Lu8fZ24EW-07FbPqENIRQwyARqs9wbJ1QY6oCTMlHoyMmvxNGIP0FzfPGYyqOx03Xnk_iQContent-Type: application/jsonapikey: 523c0c49-6e32-43a3-9c38-46d0e78d285d

vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. vuln_desc:
Description:
This alert requires manual confirmation

Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF, or XSRF) is a vulnerability wherein an attacker tricks a victim into making a request the victim did not intend to make. Therefore, with CSRF, an attacker abuses the trust a web application has with a victim's browser.

Acunetix found an HTML form with no apparent anti-CSRF protection implemented. Consult the 'Attack details' section for more information about the affected HTML form.Impact: An attacker could use CSRF to trick a victim into accessing a website hosted by the attacker, or clicking a URL containing malicious or unauthorized requests.

CSRF is a type of 'confused deputy' attack which leverages the authentication and authorization of the victim when the forged request is being sent to the web server. Therefore, if a CSRF vulnerability could affect highly privileged users such as administrators full application compromise may be possible.Request: GET /examples/servlets/servlet/SessionExample HTTP/1.1Referer: https://mscase.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.pl/healthcheckCookie: JSESSIONID=7ED94593B73AAE4329E05C98EA064526Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: mscase.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Connection: Keep-alive:

Cross site scripting (also referred to as XSS) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to send malicious code (usually in the form of Javascript) to another user.Because a browser cannot know if the script should be trusted or not, it will execute the script in the user context allowing the attacker to access any cookies or session tokens retained by the browser.Impact: Malicious users may inject JavaScript, VBScript, ActiveX, HTML or Flash into a vulnerable application to fool a user in order to gather data from them.An attacker can steal the session cookie and take over the account, impersonating the user.It is also possible to modify the content of the page presented to the user.Request: GET /transfers/total?type=GB_ECO_TRANSFER'%22()%26%25%3Cacx%3E%3CScRiPt%20%3E53Dq(9884)%3C/ScRiPt%3E HTTP/1.1Referer: https://int-anonymous-gateway.dopapp.pl/transfers/total?type=GB_ECO_TRANSFERAccept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: int-anonymous-gateway.dopapp.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Proxy-Connection: Keep-aliveContent-Type: application/json

According to PCI, "30 June 2018 is the deadline for disabling SSL/early TLS and implementing a more secure encryption protocol – TLS 1.1 or higher (TLS v1.2 is strongly encouraged) in order to meet the PCI Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) for safeguarding payment data.Impact: An attacker may be able to exploit this problem to conduct man-in-the-middle attacks and decrypt communications between the affected service and clients.Request:

vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. Description: Apache Tomcat default installation contains the "/examples" directory which has many example servlets and JSPs.Some of these examples are a security risk and should not be deployed on a production server.

vuln_name: IBM WebSphere/WebLogic application source file exposure
vuln_desc:
Description: WebSphere Application Server could allow a remote attacker to bypass security restrictions. Web-based applications, including Web services applications running on WebSphere Application Server, could disclose application specific files contained within the war file, including files under the web-inf and meta-inf directories. An attacker could exploit this vulnerability to view or execute files on the server contained within the war file. This vulnerability also affects the WebSphere administrative console when administrative security is disabled.

Users affected:
  • IBM WebSphere Application Server versions 5.1, 6.0, 6.1 and 7.0 users.
    • Impact: Application specific files are open to display and execution by an attacker.Request: GET /docs/appdev/sample/web/%2e/WEB-INF/web.xml HTTP/1.1Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: mscase.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Connection: Keep-alive:
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

vuln_desc: Description: The WEB-INF/web.xml Deployment Descriptor file describes how to deploy a web application in a servlet container such as Tomcat. Normally, this file should not be accessible. However, Acunetix WS was able to read the contents of this file by using various encodings and directory traversal variants.Impact: Configuration files will disclose sensitive information that will help a malicious user to prepare more advanced attacks.Request: GET /docs/appdev/sample/web/./WEB-INF/web.xml HTTP/1.1Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: mscase.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Connection: Keep-alive:

vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. vuln_desc:
The value of the Referer HTTP header is copied into the value of a tag attribute which can contain JavaScript. The payload javascript:alert(1)//p06lboeb was submitted in the Referer HTTP header. This input was echoed unmodified in the application's response.

This proof-of-concept attack demonstrates that it is possible to inject arbitrary JavaScript into the application's response.

Because the user data that is copied into the response is submitted within a request header, the application's behavior is not trivial to exploit in an attack against another user. In the past, methods have existed of using client-side technologies such as Flash to cause another user to make a request containing an arbitrary HTTP header. If you can use such a technique, you can probably leverage it to exploit the XSS flaw. This limitation partially mitigates the impact of the vulnerability.

vuln_desc:
The value of the Referer HTTP header is copied into a JavaScript string which is encapsulated in single quotation marks. The payload pdryo';syp1p was submitted in the Referer HTTP header. This input was echoed unmodified in the application's response.

This behavior demonstrates that it is possible to terminate the JavaScript string into which our data is being copied. An attempt was made to identify a full proof-of-concept attack for injecting arbitrary JavaScript but this was not successful. You should manually examine the application's behavior and attempt to identify any unusual input validation or other obstacles that may be in place.

Because the user data that is copied into the response is submitted within a request header, the application's behavior is not trivial to exploit in an attack against another user. vuln_desc:
Description: Cross-site Scripting (XSS) refers to client-side code injection attack wherein an attacker can execute malicious scripts into a legitimate website or web application. XSS occurs when a web application makes use of unvalidated or unencoded user input within the output it generates.Impact: Malicious JavaScript has access to all the same objects as the rest of the web page, including access to cookies and local storage, which are often used to store session tokens. If an attacker can obtain a user's session cookie, they can then impersonate that user.

Furthermore, JavaScript can read and make arbitrary modifications to the contents of a page being displayed to a user. Therefore, XSS in conjunction with some clever social engineering opens up a lot of possibilities for an attacker.Request: GET /capGui/?url=https://saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/internet-domowy%3F1P'onmouseover=PhKM(9760)' HTTP/1.1Referer: https://ssolan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/capGui/?url=https://saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/internet-domowy?1PConnection: keep-aliveCookie: JSESSIONID=64E5795957B425CC702025B3A56BF356Accept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: ssolan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

vuln_name: Cross-origin resource sharing: arbitrary origin trusted
vuln_desc:
The application implements an HTML5 cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) policy for this request that allows access from any domain.

The application allowed access from the requested origin https://cvwrnuqhecjt.com

Since the Vary: Origin header was not present in the response, reverse proxies and intermediate servers may cache it. This may enable an attacker to carry out cache poisoning attacks.
app_context: type webapp client customer domain Internet

vuln_desc:
The filter parameter appears to be vulnerable to OS command injection attacks. It is possible to use various shell metacharacters to inject arbitrary OS commands. The command output does not appear to be returned in the application's responses, however it is possible to inject time delay commands to verify the existence of the vulnerability.

The payload |ping -n 21 127.0.0.1||`ping -c 21 127.0.0.1` #' |ping -n 21 127.0.0.1||`ping -c 21 127.0.0.1` #\" |ping -n 21 127.0.0.1 was submitted in the filter parameter. The application took 22343 milliseconds to respond to the request, compared with 122 milliseconds for the original request, indicating that the injected command caused a time delay.
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

vuln_desc:
It is possible to induce the application to perform server-side DNS lookups of arbitrary domain names.

The payload qb56gzrbh19ekxr6ev8u9eusrjxcl79zxrkk89.burpcollaborator.net was submitted in the fServerName%24cControl parameter.

The application performed a DNS lookup of the specified domain.
app_context: type webapp client customer domain Internet

vuln_desc:
The URL path filename appears to be vulnerable to server-side template injection attacks. The template engine appears to be Mustache.

The payload r7am5{{.}}i0n1z{{..}}taymq was submitted in the URL path filename. This payload contains a Mustache template statement.

The server response contained the string r7am5i0n1ztaymq. This indicates that the payload is being interpreted by a server-side template engine.
app_context: type webapp client customer domain Internet

The URL path filename appears to be vulnerable to server-side template injection attacks. The template engine appears to be Mustache.

The payload egrip{{.}}ajgdh{{..}}p7kir was submitted in the URL path filename. This payload contains a Mustache template statement.

The server response contained the string egripajgdhp7kir. This indicates that the payload is being interpreted by a server-side template engine.
app_context: type webapp client customer domain Internet

The payload zl6vs{{.}}zu2ri{{..}}lgm8s was submitted in the URL path filename. This payload contains a Mustache template statement.

The server response contained the string zl6vszu2rilgm8s. This indicates that the payload is being interpreted by a server-side template engine.
app_context: type webapp client customer domain Internet

vuln_desc: Description: This page is using a weak password. Acunetix was able to guess the credentials required to access this page. vuln_desc: Description: The web server supports encryption through TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 is not considered to be "strong cryptography" as defined and required by the PCI Data Security Standard 3.2(.1) when used to protect sensitive information transferred to or from web sites. 				According to PCI, "30 June 2018 is the deadline for disabling SSL/early TLS and implementing a more secure encryption protocol – TLS 1.1 or higher (TLS v1.2 is strongly encouraged) in order to meet the PCI Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) for safeguarding payment data.Impact: An attacker may be able to exploit this problem to conduct man-in-the-middle attacks and decrypt communications between the affected service and clients.Request:
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

Applications often contain "cookie-forcing" conditions which make this possible, and such a condition in any related domain or subdomain can potentially be used for this purpose. Nonetheless, this limitation somewhat mitigates the impact of the vulnerability.

vuln_desc:
Description: This web application is potentially vulnerable to the BREACH attack.

An attacker with the ability to:
  • Inject partial chosen plaintext into a victim's requests
  • Measure the size of encrypted traffic
can leverage information leaked by compression to recover targeted parts of the plaintext.

BREACH (Browser Reconnaissance & Exfiltration via Adaptive Compression of Hypertext) is a category of vulnerabilities and not a specific instance affecting a specific piece of software. To be vulnerable, a web application must:

  • Be served from a server that uses HTTP-level compression
  • Reflect user-input in HTTP response bodies
  • Reflect a secret (such as a CSRF token) in HTTP response bodies
Impact: An attacker can leverage information leaked by compression to recover targeted parts of the plaintext.Request: GET /capGui/?url=https://saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/internet-domowy%3F1P9042086 HTTP/1.1Referer: https://ssolan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/capGui/?url=https://saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/internet-domowy?1PConnection: keep-aliveCookie: JSESSIONID=64E5795957B425CC702025B3A56BF356Accept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: ssolan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21

Cross site scripting (also referred to as XSS) is a vulnerability that allows an attacker to send malicious code (usually in the form of Javascript) to another user.Because a browser cannot know if the script should be trusted or not, it will execute the script in the user context allowing the attacker to access any cookies or session tokens retained by the browser.Impact: Malicious users may inject JavaScript, VBScript, ActiveX, HTML or Flash into a vulnerable application to fool a user in order to gather data from them.An attacker can steal the session cookie and take over the account, impersonating the user.It is also possible to modify the content of the page presented to the user.Request: GET /simpleProductOrder/list?mode=1'%22()%26%25%3Cacx%3E%3CScRiPt%20%3ExlfS(9815)%3C/ScRiPt%3E HTTP/1.1Referer: https://dev-public-gateway.dopapp.pl/simpleProductOrder/listAccept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: dev-public-gateway.dopapp.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/73.0.3683.103 Safari/537.36Proxy-Connection: Keep-aliveapikey: 523c0c49-6e32-43a3-9c38-46d0e78d285dContent-Type: application/jsonAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCIgOiAiSldUIiwia2lkIiA6ICJBUTVpRk5fUTgwc2Fybm56dkVWLXkyTlIzZXpZV0JVTDd5SHgwSDNiVnFRIn0..YfM_-_D-AUyxc_ij2fADiRyoICWUj5d6ES9O19_CSz3PmFbNZg5vkxDNVYZCOXR4zPaRCtYFv1eupZsH35veNQhqjP0SJcv1QYgJG2gzwA2MeuTPjclNZNXS4r1BWUajrZVbBJag1ocKC4UgyxfIq5E2JamjaNOYd3BQZAaWLvm3WsK6L15v5BNRG9X691uJ5sY4GPSIn31-ndiPrEVcWeisY0Zua2Bmvcha4s_tTYmZSX67RdVFrOCRHUxGqVeLmuYKIeN_LTwY8o0RjXc-i8BIMQZ9UsGBdZTR6AN_Yx0NbN_rn1iT78e0tj7mJ-VEOFmSzUNpdRtT2pk1icy-cw

vuln_desc:
Description:
This alert requires manual confirmation

Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF, or XSRF) is a vulnerability wherein an attacker tricks a victim into making a request the victim did not intend to make. Therefore, with CSRF, an attacker abuses the trust a web application has with a victim's browser.

Acunetix found an HTML form with no apparent anti-CSRF protection implemented. Consult the 'Attack details' section for more information about the affected HTML form.Impact: An attacker could use CSRF to trick a victim into accessing a website hosted by the attacker, or clicking a URL containing malicious or unauthorized requests.

CSRF is a type of 'confused deputy' attack which leverages the authentication and authorization of the victim when the forged request is being sent to the web server. Therefore, if a CSRF vulnerability could affect highly privileged users such as administrators full application compromise may be possible.Request: POST /capGui/?url=https://saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.pl/internet-domowy%253F1P HTTP/1.1Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencodedCookie: JSESSIONID=64E5795957B425CC702025B3A56BF356;SAMLRequest=1;RelayState=1Accept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateContent-Length: 573Host: ssolan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21Connection: Keep-aliveauthenticationMethod=&chosenAuthenticationMethod=1&encryptedParameters=PTxI8q2QyieKDcg1JHXtj/lbV5bOwP8iIlUZyyqM9tjAWGcYNqfQRzeJ5OZsEfPw5xg4QKZ4jth9vQjDKtbyTxKgxAMdD8wGfiOQ1HYnOFtc9ZUZHBUmw6HnuoRA9%2Bp8QzDltwidxFy3BEmoUUPpPc3wQnh3ikla8VY0cKwuOSHcm9Vd4IO7CGoRB1r5YSWLDd/W0AmqVOVBQ3VLd6K7Z5E5vdp09Kh/y3ykkn4JbwJ7Uw7KthDCgASYH1J/UPsEjeLvwn3J4OKFFwAy75H03yx5xc2%2BPQWhoFcwZrMIuqU=&isActive=true&loginParameters['RelayState']=1&loginParameters['SAMLRequest']=1&loginParameters['passwordChangeWasSuccessful']=1&queryParameters=1&requestTokenId=a026f9b8-4e93-4391-9671-7e702dbbdb86

vuln_desc:
Description: Apache Tomcat default installation contains the "/examples" directory which has many example servlets and JSPs.Some of these examples are a security risk and should not be deployed on a production server.
The Sessions Example servlet (installed at /examples/servlets/servlet/SessionExample) allows session manipulation. Because the session is global this servlet poses a big security risk as an attacker can potentitally become an administrator by manipulating its session.Impact: Bypassing HttpOnly Cookies protection, CSRF cookies manipulation, Session manipulation.Request: GET /examples/servlets/servlet/SessionExample HTTP/1.1Connection: keep-aliveAccept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: helloorange.dockerpregl.k9s.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

vuln_desc:
Description: Clickjacking (User Interface redress attack, UI redress attack, UI redressing) is a malicious technique of tricking a Web user into clicking on something different from what the user perceives they are clicking on, thus potentially revealing confidential information or taking control of their computer while clicking on seemingly innocuous web pages.

The server didn't return an X-Frame-Options header which means that this website could be at risk of a clickjacking attack. The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page inside a frame or iframe. Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.Impact: The impact depends on the affected web application. Request: GET / HTTP/1.1Connection: keep-aliveAccept: */*Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflateHost: saleslan.tr.omnitest.corpnet.plUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.21 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2228.0 Safari/537.21streetId: 86217line2: 108preZipCode: 40postalCode: 858line1: Brackacity: 93099town: Katowice
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP

vuln_desc: Description: The web server supports encryption through TLS 1.0. TLS 1.0 is not considered to be "strong cryptography" as defined and required by the PCI Data Security Standard 3.2(.1) when used to protect sensitive information transferred to or from web sites. 				According to PCI, "30 June 2018 is the deadline for disabling SSL/early TLS and implementing a more secure encryption protocol – TLS 1.1 or higher (TLS v1.2 is strongly encouraged) in order to meet the PCI Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) for safeguarding payment data.Impact: An attacker may be able to exploit this problem to conduct man-in-the-middle attacks and decrypt communications between the affected service and clients.Request:
app_context: type webapp client employe domain LANWANCPDF0TP
